<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!-- Section fragment: xi:included by the standalone deck AND by main.ptx.
     Revised: tighter flow, split-line equations (reveal clips wide math),
     combined speed+density slide, static TikZ helix figure (replaces the
     Plotly interactive), and a closing recap slide. -->
<section xml:id="sec-line-integrals">
  <title>Line Integrals of Scalar Functions</title>

  <slide>
        <title>Motivation: the mass of a curved wire</title>

        <p>
          Goal: find the mass of a wire that is <em>not</em> a simple straight
          line, whose density <m>\rho(x,y,z)</m> varies from point to point.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a straight wire of constant density,
          <m>\text{mass}=\text{density}\times\text{length}</m>. Here, neither
          shortcut applies.
        </p>
        <p>
          <alert>Strategy.</alert> Chop the wire into tiny pieces, multiply each
          piece's density by its length, and add up the results.
        </p>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>A Riemann sum along the wire</title>

        <p>
          Represent the wire by a curve <m>C</m> parametrized by
          <m>t\in[a,b]</m>, and divide it into <m>n</m> small portions. The
          <m>k</m>th portion has length <m>\Delta s_k</m> and a sample point
          <m>(x_k,y_k,z_k)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          On a short portion the density is nearly constant, so
          <me>\text{mass of the }k\text{th portion}\approx \rho(x_k,y_k,z_k)\,\Delta s_k,</me>
          and summing over all portions,
          <me>\text{mass of the wire}\approx \sum_{k=1}^{n} \rho(x_k,y_k,z_k)\,\Delta s_k.</me>
        </p>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>The wire, partitioned</title>

        <figure>
          <caption>
            A wire as a curve <m>C</m>, <m>t\in[a,b]</m>. The highlighted
            portion has length <m>\Delta s_k</m>; the dotted position vector
            <m>\vr(t_k)</m> locates its sample point <m>(x_k,y_k,z_k)</m>.
          </caption>
          <image xml:id="li-wire-partition" width="70%">
            <shortdescription>
              A space curve with one small highlighted portion and a dotted
              position vector reaching it from the origin.
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
              \definecolor{paper}{HTML}{F3F2F2}
              \definecolor{gold}{HTML}{B68235}
              \definecolor{mutedp}{HTML}{8F8C87}
              \begin{axis}[
                  width=11cm, view={115}{18},
                  xlabel={\(x\)}, ylabel={\(y\)}, zlabel={\(z\)},
                  xmin=-1.3, xmax=1.3, ymin=-1.3, ymax=1.3, zmin=0, zmax=1.7,
                  grid=major, grid style={mutedp!35},
                  axis line style={mutedp},
                  ticklabel style={color=mutedp},
                  every axis label/.append style={color=paper},
                  clip=false,
                ]
                % the wire C, before and after the k-th portion
                \addplot3[paper, very thick, domain=0:1.8, samples=80, samples y=0]
                    ({cos(deg(x))}, {sin(deg(x))}, {x/2});
                \addplot3[paper, very thick, domain=2.0:3, samples=60, samples y=0]
                    ({cos(deg(x))}, {sin(deg(x))}, {x/2});
                % the k-th portion, of length Delta s_k
                \addplot3[gold, line width=2.2pt, domain=1.8:2.0, samples=20, samples y=0]
                    ({cos(deg(x))}, {sin(deg(x))}, {x/2});
                % position vector r(t_k) from the origin to the sample point
                \addplot3[-&gt;, gold, densely dotted, thick] coordinates {(0,0,0) (-0.3233,0.9463,0.95)};
                % endpoints and sample point
                \addplot3[only marks, mark=*, gold, mark size=1.5pt] coordinates
                    {(1,0,0) (-0.98999,0.14112,1.5) (-0.3233,0.9463,0.95)};
                \node[anchor=north west, xshift=8pt, yshift=-2pt, paper] at (axis cs:1,0,0) {\(t=a\)};
                \node[above left, paper] at (axis cs:-0.98999,0.14112,1.5) {\(t=b\)};
                \node[right=2pt, gold] at (axis cs:-0.3233,0.9463,0.95) {\(\Delta s_k\)};
                \node[left=2pt, paper] at (axis cs:-0.3233,0.9463,0.98) {\((x_k,y_k,z_k)\)};
                \node[right=2pt, gold] at (axis cs:-0.16,0.47,0.475) {\(\mathbf r(t_k)\)};
                \node[paper, right=5pt] at (axis cs:0.878,0.479,0.25) {\(C\)};
              \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>From sum to integral</title>

        <p>
          The sum is only an approximation. It becomes exact in the limit
          <m>\Delta s_k\to 0</m> (equivalently <m>n\to\infty</m>):
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{mass of the wire} \amp = \lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=1}^{n} \rho(x_k,y_k,z_k)\,\Delta s_k</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \int_C \rho(x,y,z)\,ds.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          This limit is the <term>scalar line integral</term>, read
          <q>the integral of <m>\rho</m> over the curve <m>C</m>.</q>
        </p>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>Writing <m>ds</m> in terms of <m>dt</m></title>

        <p>
          To evaluate the integral, express the line element <m>ds</m> using
          the parameter. As with arc length, <m>ds</m> is the length of an
          infinitesimal displacement:
          <me>ds=\sqrt{(dx)^2+(dy)^2+(dz)^2}.</me>
          Factoring out <m>dt</m>,
          <me>\text{mass}=\int_C \rho\sqrt{\left(\tfrac{dx}{dt}\right)^2+\left(\tfrac{dy}{dt}\right)^2+\left(\tfrac{dz}{dt}\right)^2}\,dt.</me>
        </p>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>The tidy form</title>

        <p>
          The square root is exactly the length of the velocity vector
          <me>\vv(t)=\vr'(t)=\left\langle \tfrac{dx}{dt},\ \tfrac{dy}{dt},\ \tfrac{dz}{dt}\right\rangle,</me>
          so the formula becomes
          <me>\text{mass}=\int_a^b \rho\bigl(x(t),y(t),z(t)\bigr)\,\lVert \vr'(t)\rVert\,dt.</me>
        </p>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>The general scalar line integral</title>

        <p>
          Nothing was special about density. For any scalar function <m>f</m>
          along a curve <m>C</m> parametrized by <m>\vr(t)</m>, <m>a\le t\le b</m>,
          <me>\int_C f\,ds=\int_a^b f\bigl(x(t),y(t),z(t)\bigr)\,\lVert \vr'(t)\rVert\,dt.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          In words: <em>trade the geometric element <m>ds</m> for the parameter
          element <m>\lVert\vr'(t)\rVert\,dt</m>.</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          <alert>Sanity checks.</alert> Taking <m>f=1</m> recovers the arc length
          <m>\int_C ds=\int_a^b\lVert\vr'(t)\rVert\,dt</m>; and
          <m>\lVert\vr'(t)\rVert</m> is the speed <m>|\vv(t)|</m>.
        </p>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>Example: mass and length of a helical wire</title>

        <example>
          <statement>
            <p>
              A helix-shaped wire has its bottom end at <m>(1,0,0)</m> and
              parametric equation
              <me>\vr(t)=\langle \cos t,\ \sin t,\ t\rangle,\qquad t\ge 0.</me>
              Its density is <m>\rho(x,y,z)=4x^2y^2</m> kg/m. Given the mass
              <m>m=\dfrac{\pi}{2\sqrt{2}}</m> kg, calculate the length <m>\ell</m>
              of the wire.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </example>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>The plan</title>

        <p>
          The wire occupies the part of the helix with <m>0\le t\le b</m>, where
          the upper limit <m>b</m> marks where the wire ends <mdash/> and it is
          unknown.
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use the known mass
                <m>m=\displaystyle\int_0^{b}\rho\,\lVert\vr'(t)\rVert\,dt</m>
                to find <m>b</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Then the length is the arc length
                <m>\ell=\displaystyle\int_0^{b}\lVert\vr'(t)\rVert\,dt</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>Speed and density along the helix</title>

        <p>
          Differentiate and take the length:
          <md>
            <mrow>\vr'(t) \amp = \langle -\sin t,\ \cos t,\ 1\rangle,</mrow>
            <mrow>\lVert\vr'(t)\rVert \amp = \sqrt{\sin^2 t+\cos^2 t+1}=\sqrt{2}.</mrow>
          </md>
          The speed is the constant <m>\sqrt{2}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Along the curve, using <m>2\sin t\cos t=\sin(2t)</m>, the density becomes
          <me>\rho=4x^2y^2=(2\sin t\cos t)^2=\sin^2(2t).</me>
        </p>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>Solving for the upper limit <m>b</m></title>

        <p>
          Using the half-angle identity
          <m>\sin^2(2t)=\tfrac12\bigl(1-\cos(4t)\bigr)</m>,
          <md>
            <mrow>m \amp=\sqrt{2}\int_0^{b}\sin^2(2t)\,dt=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\int_0^{b}\bigl(1-\cos(4t)\bigr)\,dt</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(b-\tfrac14\sin(4b)\right).</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Setting this equal to <m>\dfrac{\pi}{2\sqrt{2}}</m>, and noting
          <m>\sin(2\pi)=0</m>:
          <me>b-\tfrac14\sin(4b)=\frac{\pi}{2}\quad\Longrightarrow\quad b=\frac{\pi}{2}.</me>
        </p>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>The length of the wire</title>

        <p>
          Because the speed is the constant <m>\sqrt{2}</m>,
          <me>\ell=\int_0^{\pi/2}\lVert\vr'(t)\rVert\,dt=\sqrt{2}\int_0^{\pi/2}dt=\frac{\pi}{\sqrt{2}}\approx 2.22\text{ m}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          About <m>2.22</m> meters <mdash/> a quarter turn of the helix, from
          <m>(1,0,0)</m> up to <m>(0,1,\pi/2)</m>.
        </p>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>The quarter-turn helix</title>

        <figure>
          <caption>
            The helical wire <m>\vr(t)=\langle\cos t,\sin t,t\rangle</m> for
            <m>0\le t\le \pi/2</m>, from <m>(1,0,0)</m> to <m>(0,1,\pi/2)</m>.
            The dashed curve is its shadow on the plane <m>z=0</m>
            (drag to rotate, scroll to zoom).
          </caption>
          <interactive xml:id="helix-wire" width="94%" aspect="4:3" iframe="helix-wire.html">
            <shortdescription>
              Interactive 3D graph of the quarter-turn helix rising from
              (1,0,0) to (0,1,pi/2), with its shadow on the plane z=0.
              Drag to rotate, scroll to zoom.
            </shortdescription>
          </interactive>
        </figure>
      </slide>

  <slide>
        <title>Recap: the recipe</title>

        <p>
          <me>\int_C f\,ds=\int_a^b f\bigl(x(t),y(t),z(t)\bigr)\,\lVert \vr'(t)\rVert\,dt</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li><p>Parametrize <m>C</m> by <m>\vr(t)</m>, <m>a\le t\le b</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Compute the speed <m>\lVert\vr'(t)\rVert</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Express <m>f</m> along the curve: <m>f\bigl(x(t),y(t),z(t)\bigr)</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Integrate in <m>t</m> <mdash/> geometry traded for one ordinary integral.</p></li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </slide>
</section>
